What is the difference between perplexity and accuracy as evaluation metrics for language models? 
first explain what is perplexity and accuracy then tell the difference

What is Accuracy?

Accuracy is the easiest metric to understand.

Definition

Accuracy measures how many predictions the model got exactly correct.

Formula:

Accuracy=
Total Predictions /
Correct Predictions
Example 1

Suppose an LLM predicts the next word.

Sentence:

I drink ___

Correct word:

coffee

Model predicts:

coffee

✅ Correct









Step 2: What is Perplexity?

Perplexity is the most common training metric for language models.

Instead of asking

"Did the model predict the correct word?"

it asks

"How confident was the model about the correct next word?"

Intuition

Suppose I ask you

Finish this sentence:

I drink ______

You think

Word	Probability
coffee	0.80
tea	0.15
water	0.03
laptop	0.0001

You're very confident.

This should give

Low Perplexity

Now suppose the probabilities are

Word	Probability
coffee	0.10
tea	0.10
car	0.10
tree	0.10
phone	0.10
...	...

You're confused.

The model is uncertain.

This gives

High Perplexity.




Difference Between Accuracy and Perplexity
| Accuracy                                           | Perplexity                                               |
| -------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------- |
| Measures exact correctness                         | Measures confidence in predicting the correct next token |
| Higher is better                                   | Lower is better                                          |
| Used for classification and exact-match evaluation | Used to evaluate language models during training         |
| Ignores prediction probabilities                   | Uses the full probability distribution                   |
| 100% = perfect                                     | 1 = perfect (theoretical minimum)                        |

